, and the islands of Micronesia. The essays in this volume commemorate these diasporic experiences within the geopolitical context of East Asia. Using primary sources and oral history, individual contributors examine how Okinawan identity was constructed in the various countries to which Okinawans migrated, and how their experiences were shaped by the Japanese nation-building project and by globalization. Essays explore the return to Okinawan sovereignty, or what Nobel Laureate Oe Kenzaburo called an "impossible possibility," and the role of the Okinawan labor diaspora in Japan's imperial expansion into the Philippines and Micronesia. Contributors: Arakaki Makoto, Robert K. Arakaki, Hokama Shuzen, Edith M. Kaneshiro, Ronald Y. Nakasone, Nomura Koya, Shirota Chika, Tomiyama Ichiro, Wesley Ueunten.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aRyukyuanszForeign countries. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aArakaki, Robert K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChika, Shirota, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIchirō, Tomiyama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaneshiro, Edith M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKōya, Nomura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakoto, Arakaki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakasone, Ronald Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakasone, Ronald Y., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShBzen, Hokama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUeunten, Wesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 200